AB  - The mating and clutch development success of Colostethus stepheni, a small dendrobatid frog with terrestrial development and parental care, was studied in both primary and secondary amazonian forests, near Manaus, Brazil. Males mated twice on average, but their size influenced neither their mating frequency nor the number of eggs and tadpoles preyed upon. Individual clutches contained approximately four eggs and their survival rate (until the completion of metamorphosis) was approximately 50%. Multiple clutches were present. Predation was the principal cause of death of eggs and tadpoles. The number of eggs and tadpoles preyed upon in primary forest was approximately 10% larger than in secondary forest. During the two-year study, the number of eggs and tadpoles preyed upon was positively correlated with rainfall, although the number of clutches produced was not.
